occurrences.line_text: For Asclepiodate him ouercame,
His sonne was Elfinell, who ouercame
But what reward had he, that ouercame?
All couerd with thick woods, that quite it ouercame.
Where late he left the Beast, he ouercame,
And left the fire; loue money ouercame:
So that with finall force them all he ouercame.
The day with cloudes was suddeine ouercast,
The other all with siluer ouercast;
Their armes abroad, with gray mosse ouercast,
A foggy mist, that ouercast the day,
Both charet swift and huntsman ouercast.
As mountaine doth the valley ouercast.
The valley did with coole shade ouercast,
As when a foggy mist hath ouercast
And the faire welkin fowly ouercast,
Confounds both land & seas, and skyes doth ouercast.
But that it all the skie doth ouercast
A watry cloud doth ouercast the skie,
For though this cloud haue now me ouercast,
By this the day with dampe was ouercast,
That in the very dore him ouercaught,
But sith this wretched woman ouercome
Was ouercome of thing, that did him please;
As ouercome with too exceeding might,
And say, that I not ouercome do dye,
And yet though ouercome in haplesse fight,
Slaying Traherne, and hauing ouercome
For being ouercome by her in fight,
So was he ouercome, not ouercome,
So was he ouercome, not ouercome,
Since that he was not forst, nor ouercome in fight?
But Hercules them all did ouercome in fight.
All ouercome with infinite affect,
Of whom they ouer-comen, were depriu'd
As ouercomen of the spirites powre,
Prince Arthure ouercomes the great
Prince Arthure ouercomes Disdaine,
And ouercommen kept in prison long,
But she faire Lady ouercommen quight
And doubly ouercommen, her ador'd:
By whose entreatie both they ouercommen,
Then gan the villein him to ouercraw,
As one with griefe and anguishe ouercum,
To sinfull men with darknes ouerdight,
And ouerflow each plaine and lowly dale:
From the high mountaines, threats to ouerflow
And aye the cups their bancks did ouerflow,
And largely ouerflow the fruitfull plaine,
Else would the waters ouerflow the lands,
And looke then how much it doth ouerflow,
And all this land with endlesse losse to ouerflow.
The happy peace, which there doth ouerflow,
And ouerflow'd all countries farre away,
And ouerflowed all the field around;
And ouerflowed all the fertill plaine,
The bankes are ouerflowen, when stopped is the flood.
And now by fortune it was ouerflowne:
Or of the fruitfull liquor ouerflowne,
And Xanthus sandy bankes with bloud all ouerflowne.
The place there ouerflowne, seemd like a sodaine flood.
And to the Saxons ouer-giue their gouernment.
That with his powre he all doth ouergo,
That in short time his face they ouergrew,
The which vnused rust did ouergrow:
All ouergrowen with rude and rugged haire;
Nor any footing fynde for ouergrowen gras.
Was ouergrowne with scurfe and filthy scald;
His yron coate all ouergrowne with rust,
But ouergrowne with dust and old decay,
All ouergrowne with haire, that could awhape
Which ouer-hanging, they themselues did steepe,
She ouerhent, nought moued with her piteous looke.
But Timias him lightly ouerhent,
For still she feared to be ouerhent,
And passing speede, that shortly he her ouerhent.
In hope to haue her ouerhent at last:
The hindmost in the gate he ouerhent,
There a sad cloud of sleepe her ouerkest,
And with his burdenous blowes him sore did ouerlade.
As when a cloud his beames doth ouer-lay;
And with vnequall might doe ouerlay,
That all the place with swarmes do ouerlay,
Which cunning Craftesman hand hath ouerlayd
But with pure gold it all was ouerlayd,
But ouerleapes them all, like Robucke light,
And rising vp, gan streight to ouerlooke,
Did seeme to ouerlooke the lowly vale;
Then two speares length; So mischiefe ouermatcht the wronger.
Vnto an other Canto I will ouerpas.
The anguish of his paine to ouerpasse:
Was ouerpast, and manhood well awake,
But when the furious fit was ouerpast,
But two of them the rest far ouerpast,
But quickly she it ouerpast, so soone
Whom though he saw now somewhat ouerpast,
Till the sharpe passion being ouerpast,
Betwixt two hils, whose high heads ouerplast,
But that they ouerran all parts with easie hand.
Despisd and troden downe of all that ouerran.
Sad Trowis/, that once his people ouerran,
Them sorely vext, and courst, and ouerran,
That it could ouerreach the wisest earthly wight.
Be bold: she oft and oft it ouer-red,
That none of them the feeble ouerren,
Full many Countries they did ouerronne,
And bid his faithlesse chickens ouerronne
As if he heauen and hell would ouerronne,
Is weakned, then thou doest him ouerronne:
All th'East before vntam'd did ouerronne,
Yet ouerrul'd at last, he did to me agree.
And ouerruling him in his owne rayne,
And men admyr'd his ouerruling might;
And ouerrun to tread them to the ground.
As if he would haue ouerrun him streight,
The perill of his pride, or else be ouerrun.
He in his furie all shall ouerrunne,
For hast did ouer-runne, in dust enrould,
And Tutours nouriture to ouersee.
Dissembled faire, and faynd to ouersee.
Whose hight all Ephesus did ouersee,
For pitty so to see him ouerset.
To ioy at his foole-happie ouersight:
Pardon I pray my heedlesse ouersight,
Selfe to forget to mind another, is ouersight.
Through which the rider downe doth fall through ouersight.
That ouersprad her like a puffe of wind;
Her huge long taile her den all ouerspred,
Her wanton palfrey all was ouerspred
Does ouerspred his long bras-scaly backe,
And all the world with wonder ouerspred;
Which being all with Yuy ouerspred,
That none might thorough breake, nor ouer-stride:
For as he in his rage him ouerstrooke,
Shall ouerswim the sea with many one
And Ouert gate by North: that is the bound
To after-send his foe, that him may ouertake?
Goe caytiue Elfe, him quickly ouertake,
Till her vnwares the fierce Sansloy did ouertake.
And the Robuckes in flight to ouertake,
That short reuenge the man may ouertake,
Of kindly sleepe, that did them ouertake.
If thou didst, tell me, that I may her ouertake.
That vew of eye could scarse him ouertake,
Of fayned loue, they chaunst to ouertake
His way still vnder ground, till Thamis he ouertake.
To hope (quoth he) him soone to ouertake,
At length he saw the hindmost ouertake
Till I him ouertake, or else subdew:
Thinking by speed to ouertake his flight;
There did the Prince him ouertake anone,
Ye may him ouertake in timely tyde:
Be ouertaken. Soone her garments loose
And now he her quite ouertaken had;
Vnlesse some succour had in time him ouertaken.
He had him ouertaken in his flight.
Whom ouertaking, they gan loudly bray,
Whom ouertaking, she in merry sort
Who ouertaking him did disaray,
Whom ouertaking, loude to him he cryde;
That high trees ouerthrew, and rocks in peeces tore.
But ouerthrew himselfe vnwares, and lower lay.
Raisd warre, and him in battell ouerthrew:
He ouerthrew through his owne valiaunce;
And with her powre her owne selfe ouerthrew,
Fought with Seuerus, and him ouerthrew;
Him backward ouerthrew, and downe him stayd
And ouerthrew his bowle disdainfully;
But weenedst thou what wight thee ouerthrew,
His wicked bookes in hast he ouerthrew,
Then ere his hand he reard, he ouerthrew
And ouerthrew, what euer came her neare,
That oftentimes him nigh he ouerthrew:
He like a swarme of flyes them ouerthrew;
Whom with sore hauocke soone they ouerthrew,
That to the ground him quite she ouerthrew,
That all his other honour ouerthrew.
The raskall manie soone they ouerthrew,
But he them ouerthrew both man and horse,
That great Alcides whilome ouerthrew,
That stop out of the way to ouerthroe,
As steele can wound, or strength can ouerthroe.
And said, Deare dame, your suddein ouerthrow
That with the wind it did him ouerthrow,
That strongest Oake might seeme to ouerthrow.
Till that dread Dragon all did ouerthrow.
To ouerthrow him strongly did assay,
Gainst fort of Reason, it to ouerthrow:
Does ouerthrow, and troublous warre proclame:
Thinking to ouerthrow and downe him tred:
Doth ouerthrow the Bowre of blisse,
And him enriched through the ouerthrow
And many a priuate oft doth ouerthrow.
How she might ouerthrow the things that Concord wrought.
To ouerthrow my state and dignitie.
The sad effect of her neare ouerthrow;
The other it with force doth ouerthrow,
Whom he did ouerthrow by yonder foord,
Hath ioyn'd one euill, which doth ouerthrow
Quite ouerthrow, who now ginnes to despize
To ouerthrow, but to supplant by slight.
Vaine others ouerthrowes, who selfe doth ouerthrowe.
Into the same the knight backe ouerthrowen, fell.
Whose luckelesse riders late were ouerthrowen;
The third him ouerthrowes, and gayns
Vaine others ouerthrowes, who selfe doth ouerthrowe.
Treads downe and ouerthrowes. Now had the Carle
Into the which whomso he ouerthrowes,
In which his might was neuer ouerthrowne,
That could haue ouerthrowne a stony towre,
When suddein vp the villein ouerthrowne,
He on the table dasht, as ouerthrowne,
Were ouerthrowne and layd on th'earth full cold,
At last they haue all ouerthrowne to ground
Sayd Calidore, and to be ouerthrowne.
By strength haue ouerthrowne a stubborne steare,
And her before was seated ouerthwart
Her soone he ouertooke, and bad to stay,
And soone him ouertooke in sad perplexitie.
And shortly ouertooke: I breathing yre,
But none of all those curses ouertooke
Him ouertooke, before he came in vew.
It was not long, before he ouertooke
Of death, the which them almost ouertooke,
And pangs of death her spirit ouertooke.
But Talus soone him ouertooke, and backward drew.
Them ouertooke, and their faire blossomes blasted,
His side all bare and naked ouertooke,
Him ouertooke in middest of his race:
Ere long he ouertooke, and forst to stay,
Him in a narrow place he ouertooke,
He scorned in his ouerweening pryde;
Along the strond, which as she ouer-went,
Thought with his speare him quight haue ouerwent.
And ouer-wrestled his strong enemie,
Was ouer-wrought, and shapes of naked boyes,
The youthfull knight could not for ought be staide,
Long way he trauelled, before he heard of ought.
Or wonted feare of doing ought amis,
If that of such a Ladie she could tellen ought.
Or ought haue done, that ye displeasen might,
But followes her farre off, ne ought he feares,
Or if ought higher were then that, did it desyre.
But th'Elfin knight, which ought that warlike wage,
Then Vna gan to aske, if ought he knew,
Ne wanted ought, to shew her bounteous or wise.
Ne ought the powre of mighty men did dread
Ne ought his sturdie strokes might stand afore,
Therefore I ought craue pardon, till I there haue beene.
Let nought be hid from me, that ought to be exprest.
For all I did, I did but as I ought.
Gan smyle on them, that rather ought to weepe,
Ne ought he car'd, whom he endamaged
Ne ought the prayse of prowesse more doth marre,
Such entertainment base, ne ought would eat,
Ne ought would speake, but euermore did seeme
Or think, that ought those puissant hands may marre:
Ne ought mote euer sinke downe to the bottome there.
Was next adioyning, ne them parted ought:
Or ought that else your honour might maintaine,
Mote ought allay the storme of your despight,
But ere the point arriued, where it ought,
To vse that sword so wisely as it ought.
Not good nor seruiceable else for ought,
Ne ought I weene are ye therein behind,
But if ought else that I mote not deuise,
To reach, when euer he for ought did send;
Liues ought, that to her linage may compaire,
Yet ceased not the bloudy fight for ought;
Ought thy remembraunce, and perpetuall band
And fairely feasted, as so noble knights she ought.
And letteth her that ought the scepter weeld,
Ne ought saue perill, still as he did pas:
Or Eden selfe, if ought with Eden mote compaire.
Ne ought, that did to his aduauncement tend,
Ne ought their goodly workmanship might saue
If ought amis her liking may abuse:
Ne ought the more their mightie strokes surceasse,
And her knights seruice ought, to hold of her in fee.
The noble courage neuer weeneth ought,
Therein discouered was, ne ought mote pas,
Ne ought in secret from the same remaynd;
My raging smart, ne ought my flame relent,
Ne ought it mote the noble Mayd auayle,
As if ought in this world in secret store
Yet ought mens good endeuours them confirme,
Ne ought ye want, but skill, which practize small
And sooth, it ought your courage much inflame,
Her noble deeds, ne her right course for ought forsooke.
When she for ought him sharpely did reproue,
Much feared he, least ought did ill betide
Or fairer then her selfe, if ought algate
Ne ought your burning fury mote abate;
Of readie entrance, which ought euermore
Or ought your goodly patience offend,
Ne euer is he wont on ought to feed,
This all as bad as she, and worse, if worse ought were.
To better boot, but let me dye, that ought;
Ne ought but deare Bisaltis ay could make him glad.
Is death, or if that ought do death exceed,
Her sword high ouer him, if ought he did offend.
For thy, they ought not thing vnknowne reproue,
As old and crooked and not good for ought.
But rather ought in friendship for her sake
That chaleng'd ought in Florimell, saue they alone.
Which Ladies ought to loue, and seeke for to obtaine.
For ought that Glauce could or doe or say.
This hand may helpe, or succour ought supplie,
Shall death be th'end, or ought else worse, aread.
Ne ought mote make him change his wonted tenor,
Ne ought mote ease or mitigate his paine,
For ought will from his greedie pleasure spare:
Whereto full loth was he, ne would for ought
Ne lend an eare to ought, that might behoue,
Certes her losse ought me to sorrow most,
For ought that euer she could doe or say,
Ne euer ought but of their true loues talkt,
Ne ought on earth that merry is and glad,
Ne ought on earth that louely is and fayre,
Or ought more hard, then thinke to reckon right.
Then let mee liue, as louers ought to do,
If ought lay hidden in his grieued thought,
And wested twice, where he ought rise aright.
Ne would for ought obay, as did become,
Ne ought the water cooled their whot bloud,
So ought each Knight, that vse of perill has,
Might otherwise preuaile, or make him cease for ought.
If ought he had the same to counterpoys.
Ne is the earth the lesse, or loseth ought,
Yet nought they could him hurt, ne ought dismay.
He long astonisht stood, ne ought he sayd,
Ne ought he did, but with fast fixed eies
Ne of that goodly hew remayned ought,
So ought all faytours, that true knighthood shame,
Therefore it ought be rendred her without deniall.
For ought or nought be wonne vnto her will,
Can dread of ought your dreadlesse hart withhold,
For little lust had she to talke of ought,
Or ought to heare, that mote delightfull bee;
But she ne would vndressed be for ought,
Ne feed on ought, the which doth bloud containe,
Can from th'immortall Gods ought hidden bee?
And therefore ought it haue, where euer she it fond.
Could ought on earth so wondrous change haue wrought,
Could so great courage stouped haue to ought?
Ne once for ought her speedy passage stayd,
Ne ought auayled for the armed knight,
Nor of ought else, that may be richest red,
Did to her myld obeysance, as they ought,
Saying; Deare Lady, deedes ought not be scand
All perill ought be lesse, and lesse all paine
Dye rather, then doe ought, that mote dishonour yield.
Knights ought be true, and truth is one in all:
Is ought on earth so pretious or deare,
As prayse and honour? Or is ought so bright
Ne ought to answere thereunto did find;
Ne ought could them endure, but all they cleft or brast.
As if that long she had not eaten ought;
Ne ought dismayed was Sir Calidore,
Or low beneath, yet ought they well to know
Of perill, or of ought that might befall:
There of the Knight, the which that Castle ought,
To safeconduct his loue, and not for ought
Fearelesse, who ought did thinke, or ought did say,
Fearelesse, who ought did thinke, or ought did say,
Yet would he not perswaded be for ought,
When ought he did, that did their lyking gaine.
It euer to amend: ne maruaile ought;
And where is eke your friend, which halfe it ought?
But she thereto nould plead, nor answere ought
Ne ought it mote auaile her to entreat
Ne ought that foole for pitty did him spare,
Who was so far from being ought amazed,
Fearelesse of ought, that mote her peace molest,
Ne ought was tyred with his endlesse toyles,
Ne ought was feared of his certaine harmes:
Of clothes to couer, what they ought by kind:
Ne ought in all that world of beauties rare,
Ne ought there wanted, which for pleasure might
With which none had to doe, ne ought partake,
Ne ought would buy, how euer prisd with measure,
Would not for ought be drawne to former drede,
In euery thing, thou oughtest first to know,
Banisht from liuing wights, our wearie dayes we waste.
Inquireth of our states, and of our knightly deedes.
Inquireth of our states, and of our knightly deedes.
If not well ended at our dying day.
And to the place, where all our perils dwell;
The tree of life, the crime of our first fathers fall.
Where we must land some of our passengers,
So parted we and on our iourney driue,
More rype vs reason lent to chose our Peares,
Our selues in league of vowed loue we knit:
Who first to rayse our house to honour did begin.
Which with sad cares empeach our natiue ioyes:
Thus said; Behold th'ensamples in our sights,
And of our safetie good heede to take;
The sacred soile, where all our perils grow;
Who wondrous things concerning our welfare,
That is our Selfe, whom though we do not see,
For here the end of all our trauell is:
Else she will slip away, and all our drift despise.
That she is fairer, then our fairest Dame,
(Said they) and haue our Ladies loue for his reward.
Our faulty weaknesse, and your matchlesse might:
And sayd, Sith then thou knowest all our griefe,
Pitty our plaint, and yield vs meet reliefe.
That therefore nought our passage may empeach,
Let vs in feigned armes our selues disguize,
And our weake hands (whom need new strength shall teach)
Our life is day, but death with darknesse doth begin.
He is yslaine, which is the ground of all our woe.
And tend our charges with obeisance meeke:
Turne we our steedes, that both in equall tilt
And how we with our foe may come to fight.
Till thou cam'st hither to augment our mone,
Of our like persons eath to be disguiz'd,
That as we ride together on our way,
To you, that are our iudge of equity,
Our wearie yokes, to gather fresher sprights,
To whom our sire, Milesio by name,
Which as our owne we tooke, and so it thought.
Full true it is, what so about our land
Vnto your selfe, said they, we giue our word,
That we may compasse this our enterprize?
With which he dares our offers thus despize.
But sith ye please, that both our blames shall die,
Vpon our way, to which we weren bent,
Such be our ioyes, which in these forrests grow:
They fall too short of our fraile reckonings,
All these our ioyes, and all our blisse abate;
All these our ioyes, and all our blisse abate;
For th'heauens enuying our prosperitie,
Which we might see after our selues remaine
In th'heritage of our vnhappie paine:
To leape into the same after our liues end.
Be it your owne: our rudenesse to your selfe aread.
We should our selues demeane, to low, to hie;
Spoyld all our cots, and caried vs from hence?
And balefull Oure, late staind with English blood:
Which when he knew, and felt ourfeeble harts
Next these the plenteous Ouse came far from land,
Lay forth out of thine euerlasting scryne
Till that some end they finde or in or out,
Their dam vpstart, out of her den effraide,
Cride out, Now now Sir knight, shew what ye bee,
Therewith she spewd out of her filthy maw
She poured forth out of her hellish sinke
The which at last out of the wood them brought.
He seekes out mighty charmes, to trouble sleepy mindes
Then choosing out few wordes most horrible,
And forth he cald out of deepe darknesse dred
Of those he chose out two, the falsest twoo,
A diuerse dreame out of his prison darke,
And rising forth out of her baser bowre,
As from a forge out of their burning shields,
That a large share it hewd out of the rest,
He pluckt a bough; out of whose rift there came
Then cride she out, Fye, fye, deformed wight,
O how, said he, mote I that well out find,
Her out of carelesse swowne. Her eylids blew
It fortuned out of the thickest wood
His fearefull friends weare out the wofull night,
Where haue ye bene thus long out of my sight?
He hurles out vowes, and Neptune oft doth blesse:
Out of the East the dawning day doth call:
Out of his swowning dreame he gan awake,
Till through celestiall doome throwne out of dore,
Does throw out thrilling shriekes, & shrieking cryes,
Who with the noyse awaked, commeth out,
Was out of Dianes fauour, as it then befell.
Pourd out in loosnesse on the grassy grownd,
Out of his mothers bowelles, and it made
And ere he could out of his swowne awake,
Whose many heads out budding euer new,
For seuen great heads out of his body grew,
His tayle was stretched out in wondrous length,
Hewen out of Adamant rocke with engines keene,
And stedfast truth acquite him out of all.
Out of the earth, with blade all burning bright
Large streames of bloud out of the truncked stocke
That stop out of the way to ouerthroe,
That life nigh crusht out of his panting brest:
But soone as breath out of his breast did pas,
Which there were slaine, as sheepe out of the fold,
Her teeth out of her rotten gummes were feld,
To seeke her out with labour, and long tyne,
Then linger, till the glasse be all out ronne?
Out of his hand she snatcht the cursed knife,
And when she list poure out her larger spright,
To pluck it out with pincers firie whot,
To put away out of his carefull brest.
And thou faire ymp, sprong out from English race,
Out of his stinking gorge forth steemed still,
Out of the sea faire Titans deawy face,
Out of the well, wherein he drenched lay;
As Eagle fresh out of the Ocean waue,
Where fast it stucke, ne would there out be got:
And gathering vp himselfe out of the mire,
That glauncing fire out of the yron plaid;
